# No Force Push to responsum-team/dbtproject

NEVER use `git push --force` (or `-f`) to `responsum-team/dbtproject` under any circumstances.
The secondary repo must always preserve its own history. Use the copy-and-commit sync below.

## Approved sync process (no force, no filter-repo)

```bash
source .env   # loads PAT2

# 1. Clone the secondary repo (keeps its own history)
rm -rf /tmp/dbt-sync-target
git clone "https://${PAT2}@github.com/responsum-team/dbtproject.git" /tmp/dbt-sync-target

# 2. Copy latest dbt project content on top — never delete what is already there
rsync -av \
  --exclude='.git' \
  /home/fillip/projec/cursorskills/dbt_project/drip_transformations/ \
  /tmp/dbt-sync-target/

# 3. Commit and push normally (no --force)
cd /tmp/dbt-sync-target
git add -A
git diff --cached --quiet || git commit -m "sync: update from elixirrjob1/cursorskills main"
git push
```

## What NOT to do

- `git push --force` to responsum-team/dbtproject — forbidden
- `git filter-repo` on the main repo then push — forbidden (rewrites history, requires force)
- Direct pushes from `elixirrjob1/cursorskills` to `responsum-team/dbtproject` — forbidden
